05264nam a22008655i 9789048537822DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20202020ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485378227 a10.1515/97890485378222doi  a(DE-B1597)550722  a(OCoLC)1158015759  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aPER0040002bisacsh04a725.82309412231 aVélez-Serna, Maria, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEphemeral Cinema Spaces :bStories of Reinvention, Resistance and Community /cMaria Vélez-Serna. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (228 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm Culture in Transition00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of figures -- tIntroduction -- t1. Unstable constellations: Recognizing cinema out of place -- t2. Relocations: Mapping the non-theatrical field in Scotland -- t3. A desire for the civic: Community cinemas and volunteer work -- t4. Film clubs and subcultural cinephile spaces -- t5. On the ground: Participatory screenings in everyday spaces -- t6. Crafting the extraordinary: site-specificity and liveness -- t7. Against enclosure: DIY exhibition as prefigurative action -- tCoda -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbout the author -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith changing technologies and social habits, the communal cinema experience would seem to be a legacy from another era. However, the last decade has seen a surge in interest for screening films in other, temporary public settings. This desire to turn pubs, galleries, parks, and even boats, into temporary cinema spaces is moved not only by a love for movies, but also a search for ways of being and working together. This book documents current practices of pop-up and site-specific cinema exhibition in the UK (with a focus on Scotland), tracing their links with historical forms of non-theatrical exhibition such as public hall cinema and fairground bioscopes. Through archival research, observation and interviews, the project asks how exhibitors create ephemeral social spaces, and how the combination of film and venue reinvents cinema as device and as social practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aMotion picture theaterszGreat Britainy21st century. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aCultural Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aMedia Studies. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  aNon-theatrical, cinemagoing, exhibition, pop-up cinema.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311068955608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP ROW Ebook Package English 2020z978311069630140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048537822?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048537822423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048537822/original  a978-3-11-068955-6  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-069629-5  DG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2b2020  a978-3-11-069630-1  PP ROW Ebook Package English 2020b2020 